WEBVTT

00:01.500 --> 00:03.680
Okay, the tapes were on.

00:04.340 --> 00:08.000
Mark, could you give me a little bit of your background, how you grew up,

00:08.140 --> 00:11.980
and maybe how you got interested in writing, and what kind of

00:11.980 --> 00:15.620
science backgrounds you might have had that might have pointed you towards science fiction eventually?

00:16.400 --> 00:20.420
Sure. I was born in 1946 in New Jersey,

00:21.220 --> 00:23.720
and grew up in the suburbs outside of Philadelphia.

00:24.860 --> 00:28.000
I'd say that probably my interest in the literary

00:28.000 --> 00:32.360
matters got started when I was in

00:32.360 --> 00:36.000
grade school, junior high school, my mother was a college level English teacher,

00:36.240 --> 00:39.740
taught at Penn State, I believe the University of Georgia.

00:41.720 --> 00:44.300
So I pretty much had

00:44.300 --> 00:48.060
a lot of books around at all times, and was encouraged to direct my

00:48.060 --> 00:49.680
interest in that direction.

00:52.700 --> 00:55.880
As far as starting writing goes, that was

00:56.940 --> 00:59.300
almost seemed to be the thing to do.

01:00.700 --> 01:03.820
When I was in grade school and began writing

01:03.820 --> 01:08.180
short stories, it was a good play and release for

01:08.180 --> 01:11.540
imagination, and I certainly enjoyed it, and

01:11.540 --> 01:15.240
the editors didn't share my enthusiasm, however, and I

01:15.880 --> 01:20.020
have had not entirely a lot of success in short stories, and that effect the only one

01:20.020 --> 01:24.280
I've ever published was Soul, when I finally got out here to Idaho

01:24.280 --> 01:27.340
in any event, I wrote

01:28.920 --> 01:32.400
Amateur Status as a hobby of ultra junior high and high school,

01:33.300 --> 01:37.160
and then when I got into college, I was very fortunate to go to a place called

01:37.160 --> 01:40.280
Kenyon College in Ohio, which

01:40.280 --> 01:42.920
has really quite a history.

01:45.320 --> 01:48.360
My area of study has always been

01:48.360 --> 01:52.440
the liberal arts, the sciences I'm frankly trying to be much too

01:52.440 --> 01:55.240
challenging and much too much work.

01:56.680 --> 01:59.980
What I do as a science fiction only in the sense that it's

01:59.980 --> 02:03.060
I'd say more fantasy than science fiction.

02:03.820 --> 02:07.720
I don't really have that much of a grasp of hard science, not both

02:07.720 --> 02:10.920
but I certainly appreciate the aesthetics of it,

02:12.020 --> 02:16.040
and that figures in, I take a great deal in the four novels

02:16.040 --> 02:19.140
of the effort. I was very fortunate

02:20.080 --> 02:22.340
at Kenyon because I finally decided that

02:22.340 --> 02:26.700
this was not going to sell short stories, and in my sophomore year began my first novel

02:27.640 --> 02:29.940
which was sold at the end of my junior year,

02:30.580 --> 02:34.940
and came out with paperbacks,

02:35.440 --> 02:38.980
words of starship in the fall of 1967

02:41.500 --> 02:42.540
that apparently

02:42.940 --> 02:46.360
survived in the marketplace, since being reprinted

02:48.200 --> 02:49.680
in England, Holland,

02:50.240 --> 02:54.400
not Holland, I'm sorry, England, France, Italy, and Germany.

02:56.280 --> 02:57.220
I've had the others.

02:58.900 --> 03:02.480
And I wrote another one my senior year in college.

03:03.900 --> 03:07.220
One of the Kenyon Review Prize for Achievement in Fiction, I think primarily

03:07.220 --> 03:10.340
because it was the only college student writing novel that everybody else was pulling around

03:10.340 --> 03:11.400
with poetry and short stories.

03:13.800 --> 03:15.580
I won a scholarship

03:16.480 --> 03:18.420
to the New York University Law School,

03:19.340 --> 03:23.160
a Root-Hilton scholarship, and that fact was free, pretty much determined

03:23.160 --> 03:27.600
my career choice, and because at no time was I under the illusion

03:27.600 --> 03:30.280
that gainful living could be

03:31.360 --> 03:34.780
gotten from pursuing writing. Now that's maybe either a very

03:35.400 --> 03:39.340
good, cold, rational judgment on my part, or pure cowardice

03:40.700 --> 03:42.560
in any event, I did go to New York,

03:43.360 --> 03:46.420
went through law school, wrote a third novel,

03:47.180 --> 03:50.540
the shortest one, The Days Tars There, and

03:51.840 --> 03:53.000
while I was there

03:55.060 --> 03:59.160
spent the summer of my second year with the legal department of Boise Cascade Corporation

03:59.160 --> 04:02.160
out here in Boise, met the law firm that I

04:03.420 --> 04:06.400
joined after getting out of law school, and I've been with ever since.

04:08.400 --> 04:10.080
Since coming out to Boise, I

04:11.820 --> 04:13.520
wrote just one other novel,

04:14.000 --> 04:18.240
that short story I mentioned, but one other novel, The Siege of Wonder, and that was published by

04:18.240 --> 04:21.840
Double Day in 1976, and then I think by

04:22.380 --> 04:25.100
DAW in paperback the next year, and

04:26.720 --> 04:28.560
that I think is the best so far.

04:30.800 --> 04:34.180
After that was published, I became married

04:34.180 --> 04:37.040
to a very wonderful woman, Marika,

04:38.060 --> 04:41.000
who already had two very wonderful children when I met her,

04:44.140 --> 04:45.640
and that has

04:46.080 --> 04:48.720
taken on some immediate responsibility.

04:49.900 --> 04:52.480
Also, it's become a partner in the law firm, and

04:53.560 --> 04:58.120
I've seen how everybody's, well not everybody, take that back. A lot of people expect you to be fairly

04:58.120 --> 05:02.060
grown up, fairly grown up, use the people don't like science, it doesn't

05:02.060 --> 05:05.860
mean that people don't like science fiction or reading or writing, but they do expect

05:05.860 --> 05:09.980
to pay a little more attention to the job at hand than speculating over your own personal

05:09.980 --> 05:13.880
fantasies. Anyway, for whatever reason there is, already has

05:13.880 --> 05:17.780
kind of gotten lost in the

05:17.780 --> 05:20.300
early burleys of work, and

05:20.300 --> 05:26.020
since that time I'm really embarrassed to say that I have not completed anything of any substance.

05:28.720 --> 05:29.700
The hope is still there,

05:29.700 --> 05:33.380
and I have what I believe to be,

05:33.500 --> 05:37.560
I hope will be a viable idea for another novel, and I've been

05:37.560 --> 05:39.460
pitching at it now for some time,

05:41.000 --> 05:45.400
and can speak with as much a matter of trying to find a new focus,

05:45.520 --> 05:49.700
because I believe that a lot of what I've

05:49.700 --> 05:53.140
already written was threatening to become repetitious

05:54.080 --> 05:57.160
and self-clichÃ©, and

05:57.160 --> 06:00.780
also just trying to do some new things. So that

06:01.300 --> 06:05.140
makes it perhaps a doubly difficult to get

06:05.140 --> 06:09.240
started, and to stick with it, maintain the mood, well I guess first of all I have to find the

06:09.240 --> 06:12.540
new mood before I can maintain it. And that's where it stands right now.

06:15.100 --> 06:15.580
Okay,

06:16.380 --> 06:19.820
I was laughing whenever you were talking about growing up.

06:22.500 --> 06:24.760
I'm two years younger than you, and

06:24.760 --> 06:28.480
I too have a real life job, and I don't know what it means,

06:28.700 --> 06:32.860
have to appear to be grown up anyway. What I want to do now

06:32.860 --> 06:36.440
is go back over the individual works, and

06:37.160 --> 06:40.800
see what we can dig out, the things that were interesting to discuss,

06:41.020 --> 06:42.620
and I need to turn an amplifier down.

06:44.900 --> 06:48.800
Okay, now I can hear much better. You allow that

06:48.800 --> 06:51.620
you had been writing since a fairly early age

06:52.440 --> 06:55.480
in grade school, in fact, and yet

06:55.480 --> 06:59.220
science never did, or it interested you, but not the nuts and bolts.

06:59.720 --> 07:03.320
When you did start writing, why was it science fiction and not

07:03.320 --> 07:07.340
historical fiction or mainstream novels or something else?

07:07.440 --> 07:11.660
What was the attraction of science fantasy, I guess is probably what you really write.

07:12.080 --> 07:15.620
Great, well I guess the sheer wonder of it, first of all, for an

07:15.620 --> 07:19.700
adolescent imagination, it was a very easy one to slip into.

07:19.700 --> 07:20.980
An easy

07:23.900 --> 07:27.380
genre to slip into. It did not require you to

07:27.380 --> 07:30.800
embarrass yourself particularly much by trying to do things that

07:31.530 --> 07:35.020
you had no idea how they functioned, writing about them,

07:35.780 --> 07:39.340
like girls. It provided

07:40.280 --> 07:44.040
a great deal of play, because you could allow

07:44.040 --> 07:48.120
your imagination to free reign. So I guess it was kind of self-indulgent in that sense.

07:48.900 --> 07:52.160
And that's the way that my imagination seems to work.

07:52.160 --> 07:54.540
It took a very peculiar, I thought,

07:56.100 --> 07:58.620
an individualized perspective

07:59.960 --> 08:02.160
that wanted to express some

08:03.240 --> 08:07.560
I hope of, will not turn out to have been just a limited number of

08:08.080 --> 08:11.080
ideas and feelings, and

08:12.980 --> 08:15.980
fantasy seemed to be best suited to it.

08:15.980 --> 08:19.980
Also, the combination of fantasy and

08:19.980 --> 08:21.820
science fiction allowed

08:23.940 --> 08:27.520
me to work at, even then I think,

08:29.440 --> 08:31.880
an element of irony and

08:31.880 --> 08:35.620
contradiction, which I've always enjoyed, and which is

08:35.620 --> 08:39.880
I think you've got to be pretty talented, much more than I, to do it

08:39.880 --> 08:43.720
in a real-world situation, historical or mainstream

08:43.720 --> 08:44.220
fiction.

08:47.920 --> 08:51.820
There's also another thing, I guess, for I find humor very difficult.

08:52.100 --> 08:56.360
I cry myself in normal life, having a very good sense of humor.

08:57.160 --> 08:59.760
But the writings, none of the books

08:59.760 --> 09:02.340
are at least as jolly, I'm afraid to say.

09:03.560 --> 09:07.400
And the contradiction in irony, and I suppose

09:09.360 --> 09:10.640
allowed for

09:10.640 --> 09:12.460
a reservoir of

09:15.900 --> 09:17.760
I guess, bitterness

09:19.300 --> 09:22.600
to just get out on the outside

09:22.600 --> 09:25.800
and express itself, and to operate in these

09:28.180 --> 09:29.360
half-crippled

09:30.400 --> 09:34.580
contradictory worlds that I just naturally seem drawn to.

09:37.200 --> 09:38.720
Like I said, I hope I'm not

09:38.720 --> 09:40.760
going to stay there forever, I certainly don't want to.

09:42.220 --> 09:45.600
But it had a very peculiar allure to me.

09:47.440 --> 09:50.340
And also, it was completely out of step, but what

09:50.340 --> 09:53.760
contemporary adolescent society was

09:54.740 --> 09:58.680
saying was to literally, sensitive kids ought to be

09:58.680 --> 10:00.680
doing, so they're trying to do the exact opposite.

10:02.380 --> 10:06.600
And try to offend my peers, I think I've succeeded on one more occasion when I should

10:06.600 --> 10:09.940
but that was the fortunate thing about going to Kenyon because that was very

10:10.480 --> 10:13.940
tolerant, I think, one of the two genuinely

10:14.540 --> 10:15.020
eccentric

10:18.380 --> 10:19.960
stimulating places I've been to.

10:22.040 --> 10:26.520
So that's, also, I'll bring up

10:26.520 --> 10:30.280
one more thing, the works that the books that I was reading

10:30.280 --> 10:34.660
at the time, of the novels that I was thoroughly impressed by

10:34.660 --> 10:38.840
were included to Bradbury's work and later on to College Tolkien

10:40.600 --> 10:42.500
and on TV, of course,

10:42.760 --> 10:46.080
it's very favored to Twilight Zone, that sort of thing.

10:47.500 --> 10:50.620
So it kind of cut down the conversation when you attempted to tell

10:50.620 --> 10:54.320
people what you were doing and either they weren't

10:55.080 --> 10:58.720
interested in writing at all or the kind of writing they were interested in

10:58.720 --> 11:02.440
just simply didn't match up with what this stuff was turning out as.

11:03.620 --> 11:06.660
But I just, I really enjoyed it, I felt comfortable

11:06.660 --> 11:10.640
and felt that I could do it well, I think that's

11:10.640 --> 11:11.320
probably the main reason.

11:13.780 --> 11:17.920
Okay, Lords of the Starship came out in 1967 and

11:18.440 --> 11:22.140
it was, as you mentioned, it's kind of pessimistic

11:23.300 --> 11:26.060
decadent societies, entropy is about

11:26.060 --> 11:29.900
maximized both socially and physically. That would

11:29.900 --> 11:33.640
be something which now we could, we would call

11:33.640 --> 11:37.960
probably a new wave quote unquote. Were you influenced by people

11:37.960 --> 11:41.580
like J.G. Ballard and Michael Morkock and the people that wrote them

11:41.580 --> 11:43.580
the new wave science fiction, very British?

11:43.800 --> 11:49.700
Yeah, I thoroughly impressed by Ballard's stuff, not really Morkock too much.

11:52.080 --> 11:53.020
Paul Anderson,

11:53.920 --> 11:57.140
his adventures, I remember

11:57.140 --> 12:00.940
they were quite impressive. I especially like

12:00.940 --> 12:05.040
to get back to the contradiction, the survival of

12:05.040 --> 12:08.760
what our contemporary society is, its survival

12:08.760 --> 12:12.420
into a totally unexpected, hopefully unexpected

12:14.820 --> 12:16.260
society and

12:17.100 --> 12:21.120
society of decline. That in a way, and maybe this is

12:21.120 --> 12:24.720
a cheap reason for doing it, but it allows the

12:24.720 --> 12:28.540
aesthetics of what I view to be our science

12:28.540 --> 12:31.100
and technology, even though it has failed,

12:31.900 --> 12:36.660
I certainly don't blame what happened to bring about the societies

12:36.660 --> 12:40.060
that are present in the first book, but

12:40.060 --> 12:44.520
they failed to stop them from occurring, but they did survive in

12:44.520 --> 12:48.240
fragments and I'd like to think that

12:48.240 --> 12:51.480
it acquired some kind of a tragic heroism

12:52.700 --> 12:55.300
by what they were doing. The societies,

12:55.700 --> 12:59.020
the bad societies that were in the first

12:59.020 --> 13:03.340
book, and really in the second, were really caused by whatever causes the bad

13:03.340 --> 13:04.800
society and simple stupidity.

13:08.540 --> 13:11.280
The artifacts, which if we would think

13:11.280 --> 13:15.140
back, I'm just trying to remember you're my contemporaries, so you can remember this

13:15.140 --> 13:18.560
great day of the 60s and so on. The artifacts

13:18.560 --> 13:22.740
that I enjoyed writing about, the ships in the aircraft

13:22.740 --> 13:26.680
and the devices in the science and industry, they remain

13:26.680 --> 13:30.080
in isolation. They're usually

13:30.080 --> 13:34.240
beset. The people who are allied with them are

13:34.240 --> 13:38.680
if not heroic and they're not as bad as the other folks

13:39.380 --> 13:42.080
and that kind of threw them

13:43.800 --> 13:46.260
fragments into a contract

13:46.260 --> 13:50.160
but I at least I believe made them

13:50.160 --> 13:54.080
a little on the heroic side because they battled against the inevitable

13:54.080 --> 13:55.080
and I really like that.

